{"title_page": "Edward Hain Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Edward Hain Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Cornwall Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image      = St Ives Harbour Hotel (geograph 4065263).jpg\n| Caption    = Entrance to the Edward Hain Hospital (the road on the left)\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| location   = Albany Terrace, [[St Ives, Cornwall|St Ives]], [[Cornwall]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|50.2080|-5.4793|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| map_type   =Cornwall\n| map_caption=Shown in Cornwall\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]]\n| Type       = Community\n| Speciality = \n| Helipad    = \n| Emergency  =\n| Affiliation = \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1920\n| Closed     = \n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional, autofilled [List hospitals in <State>] -->\n|}}\n'''Edward Hain Hospital''' is a health facility in Albany Terrace, [[St Ives, Cornwall|St Ives]], [[Cornwall]], England. It is managed by [[Cornwall Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility was commissioned as a memorial to Captain Edward Hain,{{efn|He was the son of [[Edward Hain|Sir Edward Hain]], the local member of parliament.}} who had died in the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref name=stratton>{{cite web|url=http://s513102927.websitehome.co.uk/files/News/CommunicationsNews/Lost_Heir_to_the_Hain_Dynasty_in_Hospitals_Naming-1.pdf|title=Lost Heir to the Hain Dynasty in Hospitals Naming|first=Vivian A. |last=Stratton |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> It was established by converting a large private property in Albany Terrace and it opened in 1920.<ref name=stratton/> It joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F216651|title=Edward Hain Hospital|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> It closed temporarily due to fire safety issues in 2016 but then re-opened as a facility for local people who have recently been discharged from hospital in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cornwallreports.co.uk/three-years-after-it-closed-patients-in-st-ives-can-still-find-a-use-for-the-edward-hain-hospital/|title=Three years after it closed, patients in St Ives can still find a use for the Edward Hain hospital|date=18 January 2019|newspaper=Cornwall Reports|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:St Ives, Cornwall]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Edward Hain Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Cornwall Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image      = St Ives Harbour Hotel (geograph 4065263).jpg\n| Caption    = Entrance to the Edward Hain Hospital (the road on the left)\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| location   = Albany Terrace, [[St Ives, Cornwall|St Ives]], [[Cornwall]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|50.2080|-5.4793|type:landmark|display=inline, title}}\n| map_type   =Cornwall\n| map_caption=Shown in Cornwall\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]]\n| Type       = Community\n| Speciality = \n| Helipad    = \n| Emergency  =\n| Affiliation = \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1920\n| Closed     = \n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional, autofilled [List hospitals in <State>] -->\n|}}\n'''Edward Hain Hospital''' is a health facility in Albany Terrace, [[St Ives, Cornwall|St Ives]], [[Cornwall]], England. It is managed by [[Cornwall Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility was commissioned as a memorial to Captain Edward Hain,{{efn|He was the son of [[Edward Hain|Sir Edward Hain]], the local member of parliament.}} who had died in the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref name=stratton>{{cite web|url=http://s513102927.websitehome.co.uk/files/News/CommunicationsNews/Lost_Heir_to_the_Hain_Dynasty_in_Hospitals_Naming-1.pdf|title=Lost Heir to the Hain Dynasty in Hospitals Naming|first=Vivian A. |last=Stratton |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> It was established by converting a large private property in Albany Terrace and it opened in 1920.<ref name=stratton/> It joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F216651|title=Edward Hain Hospital|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> It closed temporarily due to fire safety issues in 2016 but then re-opened as a facility for local people who have recently been discharged from hospital in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cornwallreports.co.uk/three-years-after-it-closed-patients-in-st-ives-can-still-find-a-use-for-the-edward-hain-hospital/|title=Three years after it closed, patients in St Ives can still find a use for the Edward Hain hospital|date=18 January 2019|newspaper=Cornwall Reports|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:St Ives, Cornwall]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Hain_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Paul Blackwell (footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh footballer}}\n{{about||the Australian actor|Paul Blackwell|the US Army officer|Paul E. Blackwell}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Paul Blackwell\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1963|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Mancot]], Wales\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1981\u20131985 \n| years2 = 1985\u2013?\n| clubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] \n| clubs2 = [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]]\n| caps1 = 94     \n| caps2 = ?      \n| goals1 = 3  \n| goals2 = ? \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| club-update = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Blackwell''' (born 13 January 1963) is a Welsh former professional footballer who nearly 100 [[The Football League|Football League]] appearances for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]], mainly as a [[Midfielder]].\n\nAlthough born in [[Flintshire]], Blackwell grew up in [[Chester]] and represented the Chester and Cheshire Schoolboys sides as a youngster.<ref name=\"programme\">Chester City vs. Exeter City matchday programme 16 March 1985, p.13</ref> Although Blackwell opted to remain at school for sixth form rather than join [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]] as an apprentice,<ref name=\"programme\"/> the club offered him a professional contract when he left school in 1981 and he was to spend the next four years at [[Sealand Road]].\n\nBlackwell made his debut for Chester in a 1\u20130 defeat at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 3 November 1981 and he went on to make 23 league appearances in each of his first two seasons in the side. The [[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384 season]] saw Chester finish bottom of [[Division Four]], but Blackwell was to enjoy regular football with 39 league appearances to his name and he scored his first goal for the club against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885\u20131997 | publisher=Yore Publications| year=1997| pages= stats section |isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref> In the summer of 1984, Blackwell became a part-time player due to combining playing with being a student at Crewe and Alsager College.<ref name=\"programme\"/> He was restricted to just nine more league outings for the club and at the end of the [[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385 season]] he moved into non-league football with [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885\u20131997 | publisher=Yore Publications| year=1997| page= 135|isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackwell, Paul}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Flintshire]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rhyl F.C. players]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Australian actor|Paul Blackwell|the US Army officer|Paul E. Blackwell}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Paul Blackwell\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1963|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Mancot]], Wales\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1981\u20131985 \n| years2 = 1985\u2013?\n| clubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] \n| clubs2 = [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]]\n| caps1 = 94     \n| caps2 = ?      \n| goals1 = 3  \n| goals2 = ? \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| manageryears1 = \n| club-update = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Blackwell''' (born 13 January 1963) is a Welsh former professional footballer who nearly 100 [[The Football League|Football League]] appearances for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]], mainly as a [[Midfielder]].\n\nAlthough born in [[Flintshire]], Blackwell grew up in [[Chester]] and represented the Chester and Cheshire Schoolboys sides as a youngster.<ref name=\"programme\">Chester City vs. Exeter City matchday programme 16 March 1985, p.13</ref> Although Blackwell opted to remain at school for sixth form rather than join [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]] as an apprentice,<ref name=\"programme\"/> the club offered him a professional contract when he left school in 1981 and he was to spend the next four years at [[Sealand Road]].\n\nBlackwell made his debut for Chester in a 1\u20130 defeat at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 3 November 1981 and he went on to make 23 league appearances in each of his first two seasons in the side. The [[1983-84 in English football|1983\u201384 season]] saw Chester finish bottom of [[Division Four]], but Blackwell was to enjoy regular football with 39 league appearances to his name and he scored his first goal for the club against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885\u20131997 | publisher=Yore Publications| year=1997| pages= stats section |isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref> In the summer of 1984, Blackwell became a part-time player due to combining playing with being a student at Crewe and Alsager College.<ref name=\"programme\"/> He was restricted to just nine more league outings for the club and at the end of the [[1984-85 in English football|1984\u201385 season]] he moved into non-league football with [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Chas Sumner | title=On the Borderline: The Official History of Chester City 1885\u20131997 | publisher=Yore Publications| year=1997| page= 135|isbn=1-874427-52-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackwell, Paul}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Flintshire]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rhyl F.C. players]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Welsh footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Welsh footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Blackwell_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Adae Kese Festival", "text_new": "'''Adae Kese Festival''' (\"big resting place\") is an important albeit rare celebration among the [[Ashanti people|Ashantis]] in Ghana.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghana.travel/events-festivals/adae-kese-festival/|title=Adae Kese Festival|last=WhiteOrange|website=Ghana Tourism Authourity|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"ghana.travel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghana.travel/events-festivals/adae-kese-festival/|title=Adae Kese Festival|last=WhiteOrange|website=Ghana Tourism Authourity|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Adae {{!}} Akan festival\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Adae|title=Adae {{!}} Akan festival|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> It glorifies the achievements of the [[Ashanti Empire|Asante]] kingdom.<ref name=Kese>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghana.travel/ghana/festivals/ada_kese_festival/ |title=Adae Kese Festival |accessdate=24 November 2012 |publisher=Official web site of Ghana.Travel Corporation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227182810/http://www.ghana.travel/ghana/festivals/ada_kese_festival/ |archivedate=27 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=African>{{Cite web|url=http://www.african.net/adaekese.htm|title= African Festivals: Adae Kese|accessdate=24 November 2012|publisher=African. Net}}</ref> It was first celebrated to the achievement of statehood of the people, after the war that the Ashantis had their independence, in the Battle of Feyiase which they fought against the people of [[Denkyira]].<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> It is also the occasion when the purification ceremony of [[Odwira festival|Odwira]] is performed at the burial shrines of ancestral spirits. Generally, this coincides with the harvest season of ''yam'' and hence the ritual was also called the \"Yam custom\" by Europeans.{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=42}} It is celebrated every two weeks by the people in accordance with the calendar of the [[Akan people|Akans]] based on the cycle of forty-two days and nine months in their calendar.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> The festival is mostly held to climax celebrations of specific achievements and milestones of the people of the [[Ashanti people|Ashanti]] kingdom.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> The festival is a day of rest so it is forbidden to work on that day.<ref name=\"Adae {{!}} Akan festival\"/>\n\n==Observance==\nIt is the annual culmination festival of the Akan calendar, the ninth [[Adae Festival]] (which occurs every six weeks). Adae Kese ushers in the New Year, with dates ranging between July and October, though some Akans like the [[Akim]], [[Akwamu]], and Ashanti celebrate New Year in January. It is also celebrated at the [[Manhyia Palace]]. It comprises rituals which is aimed purifying the spirit of the King's palace chambers by members of the royal family and other dignitaries.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe custom of holding this festival came into prominence between 1697 and 1699 when statehood was achieved for the people of Ashante after the war of independence, the [[Battle of Feyiase]], against the [[Denkyira]].<ref name=\"ghana.travel\"/> The festival was observed subsequently to the establishment of the [[Golden Stool]] (throne) in 1700. The festival was a time to consecrate the remains of the dead kings; those remains had been kept in a mausoleum at the sacred burial ground of [[Bantama]], a royal suburb of [[Kumasi]]. Adae Kese brought a link and a level of faith and solidarity between the living and the ancestral spirits. In its early times, this festival also had implications of sacrifice, both human and animal. The main festival used to be held first at Hemmaa, close to the king\u2019s palace near the location of the ancestral shrine of the kings. The second and more important part of the festival was performed at Bantama, which also was the last burial ground of the [[Asante Empire|Asante]] kings, and was known as the \u201cnotorious Bantama ritual\" as the sacrifices involved were of large proportions. When the festival was announced, by beating of drums, people went into hiding for fear that they may be selected for the human sacrifice. As part of the ritual, sheep sacrifice was also involved. Whether human sacrifice was involved or not is a subject of debate, but the fact is that the African societies considered these rites as a \"reunion between the living and the dead.\"{{Sfn|Agorsah|2010|pp=42-43}}\n\n==Traditions==\nThe Adae Kese Festival follows the same rituals as the Adae Festival, however, a difference in the celebration rites is that the chief carries a sheep for sacrifice to the [[Golden Stool|Stool]].{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=2}} The purification ceremony of [[Odwira festival|Odwira]] is celebrated during Adae Kese at the burial shrines of ancestral spirits. Generally, this coincides with the harvest season of [[Yam (vegetable)|yam]], and hence the ritual was also called the ''Yam custom'' by Europeans.{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=2}} It is celebrated at this season to thank the gods and the ancestors for a good harvest. The season is equally used to outdoor the new yam.\n\nEvery five years, the Adae Kese Festival is hosted by the paramount ruler of the Asante in the capital city of [[Kumasi]], [[Asanteman]], and lasts for two weeks.<ref name=\"AsanteMazama2008\">{{cite book|last1=Asante|first1=Molefi Kete|last2=Mazama|first2=Ama|title=Encyclopedias of African Religion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B667ATiedQkC&pg=PT36|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=26 November 2008|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-1-4129-3636-1|pages=36\u2013}}</ref> As a formal state celebration, it involves several villages and towns, within a traditional area known as ''Odwira'',<ref name=African/> uniting Ashanti from all walks of life (''Odwira'' means to purify), who attends and embrace the festival.<ref name=\"ghana.travel\"/> [[Asantehene]], the titular ruler of [[Kumasi]], holds a colourful [[durbar (court)|durbar]] of chiefs and their queens on this occasion when they all turn up in full regalia. Dancing to the beats of drums is part of the pageantry. The festival is also the occasion when people pledge their confidence in the present king of the Ashante. Some of the deserving people are given awards of recognition on this occasion. The king also holds a very private celebration within his palace chambers along with the designated members of the royal family and other officials.<ref name=Kese/>\n\n== Commentary on the Talking Drum ==\nAmong other activities that rake place on the day of the festival, the chief is carried through the streets of [[Kumasi]] in procession.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\">{{Cite web|url=https://africanpoems.net/gods-ancestors/the-adae-kese-festival/|title=The Adae Kese Festival|website=africanpoems.net|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> The following version of the drum recitation was written by [[Robert Sutherland Rattray]] in 1923:\n\n<poem>\n\"Oh, Divine Drummer,\nI am scarcely awake and have risen up.\nI, the Ashanti porcupine chief's drummer,\nI am scarcely awake.\nI have made myself to rise up,\nI am about to sound the drum,\nIf you have gone elsewhere and I call you, \nCome;\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThere are swamps, swamps, swamps,\nWhich can swallow up the elephant.\nA river may lie small in the valley\nBetween great hills.\nBut it flows on for ever and ever.\nIf you have gone elsewhere and I call upon you ( the spirit of the elephant)<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nCome.\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nI lay down, but I did not feel sleepy,\nI lay down but my eyes did not close,\nFor three watches of the night.\nI think about my friends who have left me and are asleep,\nAmoafo-Awuku-The cock-the-the old bird whose bones have grown strong.\nFowl, good morning, good morning.\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThe sky is wide, wide, wide,\nThe earth is wide, wide, wide,\nThe one was lifted up,\nThe other was set down,\nIn ancient times, long, long ago.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nSupreme Sky God, upon whom men lean and fall not,\nWe serve you.\nWhen the Sky God shows you anything\nMay you profit by it.\nIf we wish 'white' we get it,\nIf we wish 'red' we get it.\nHim upon whom we lean and do not fall,\nGod, good morning.\nYou whom we serve upon a Saturday,\nGood morning,\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThe stream crosses the path,\nThe oath crosses the stream;\nWhich of them is the elder?\nDid we not cut a path to go and meet this stream?\nThe stream had its origin long, long ago,\nThe stream had its origin in the Creator.\nHe created things,\nPure, pure Tano (refers to the Ashantis principal god)<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\nCome here, Tano;\nHe devours rams,\nTa, the great one, the powerful one\nWhom we serve upon a Monday.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nHe is coming, he is coming,\nLittle by little, slowly, slowly,\nBe careful not to stumble,\nLittle by little, slowly, slowly.\nYou will come and sit down,\nChief, you will come and sit down.\n''Kon! Kon! Kon!''\nThe great man, Osai's son, has sat down.\nThe King has sat down\nHe who destroys towns has sat down,\nHe who never forgives,\nHe has taken a stool and sat down.\"<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/></poem>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Adae Festival]]\n*[[Akwasidae Festival]]\n*[[Ashanti Yam Festival]]\n*[[Awukudae Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Agorsah |first= E. Kofi|title= Religion, Ritual and African Tradition: AfricanFoundations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wd7y1HOYeo0C&pg=PA42&dq=Adae+Kese+Festival&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HTiwUJOvJoTqmAWAqoGoBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Adae%20Kese%20Festival&f=false|accessdate=24 November 2012|year=2010|publisher= AuthorHouse |isbn=9781449005528|pages=42\u201343|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=  Roy|first=  Christian |title= Religion Traditional festivals. 2. M \u2013 Z |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKqOUfqt4cIC&pg=PA2&dq=Adae+Kese+Festival&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HTiwUJOvJoTqmAWAqoGoBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Adae%20Kese%20Festival&f=false\n|accessdate=24 November 2012|year=2005|publisher= ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781576070895|page=2|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Ashanti people]]\n[[Category:Cultural festivals in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Ashanti Region]]\n[[Category:Yam festivals]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Folk festivals in Ghana]]\n", "text_old": "'''Adae Kese Festival''' (\"big resting place\") is an important albeit rare celebration among the [[Ashanti people|Ashantis]] in Ghana.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghana.travel/events-festivals/adae-kese-festival/|title=Adae Kese Festival|last=WhiteOrange|website=Ghana Tourism Authourity|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref><ref name=\"ghana.travel\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghana.travel/events-festivals/adae-kese-festival/|title=Adae Kese Festival|last=WhiteOrange|website=Ghana Tourism Authourity|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Adae {{!}} Akan festival\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Adae|title=Adae {{!}} Akan festival|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> It glorifies the achievements of the [[Ashanti Empire|Asante]] kingdom.<ref name=Kese>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghana.travel/ghana/festivals/ada_kese_festival/ |title=Adae Kese Festival |accessdate=24 November 2012 |publisher=Official web site of Ghana.Travel Corporation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227182810/http://www.ghana.travel/ghana/festivals/ada_kese_festival/ |archivedate=27 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=African>{{Cite web|url=http://www.african.net/adaekese.htm|title= African Festivals: Adae Kese|accessdate=24 November 2012|publisher=African. Net}}</ref> It was first celebrated to the achievement of statehood of the people, after the war that the Ashantis had their independence, in the Battle of Feyiase which they fought against the people of [[Denkyira]].<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> It is also the occasion when the purification ceremony of [[Odwira festival|Odwira]] is performed at the burial shrines of ancestral spirits. Generally, this coincides with the harvest season of ''yam'' and hence the ritual was also called the \"Yam custom\" by [[Europeans]].{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=42}} It is celebrated every two weeks by the people in accordance with the calendar of the [[Akan people|Akans]] based on the cycle of forty-two days and nine months in their calendar.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> The festival is mostly held to climax celebrations of specific achievements and milestones of the people of the [[Ashanti people|Ashanti]] kingdom.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/> The festival is a day of rest so it is forbidden to work on that day.<ref name=\"Adae {{!}} Akan festival\"/>\n\n==Observance==\nIt is the annual culmination festival of the Akan calendar, the ninth [[Adae Festival]] (which occurs every six weeks). Adae Kese ushers in the New Year, with dates ranging between July and October, though some Akans like the [[Akim]], [[Akwamu]], and Ashanti celebrate New Year in January. It is also celebrated at the [[Manhyia Palace]]. It comprises rituals which is aimed purifying the spirit of the King's palace chambers by members of the royal family and other dignitaries.<ref name=\"WhiteOrange\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe custom of holding this festival came into prominence between 1697 and 1699 when statehood was achieved for the people of Ashante after the war of independence, the [[Battle of Feyiase]], against the [[Denkyira]].<ref name=\"ghana.travel\"/> The festival was observed subsequently to the establishment of the [[Golden Stool]] (throne) in 1700. The festival was a time to consecrate the remains of the dead kings; those remains had been kept in a mausoleum at the sacred burial ground of [[Bantama]], a royal suburb of [[Kumasi]]. Adae Kese brought a link and a level of faith and solidarity between the living and the ancestral spirits. In its early times, this festival also had implications of sacrifice, both human and animal. The main festival used to be held first at Hemmaa, close to the king\u2019s palace near the location of the ancestral shrine of the kings. The second and more important part of the festival was performed at Bantama, which also was the last burial ground of the [[Asante Empire|Asante]] kings, and was known as the \u201cnotorious Bantama ritual\" as the sacrifices involved were of large proportions. When the festival was announced, by beating of drums, people went into hiding for fear that they may be selected for the human sacrifice. As part of the ritual, sheep sacrifice was also involved. Whether human sacrifice was involved or not is a subject of debate, but the fact is that the African societies considered these rites as a \"reunion between the living and the dead.\"{{Sfn|Agorsah|2010|pp=42-43}}\n\n==Traditions==\nThe Adae Kese Festival follows the same rituals as the Adae Festival, however, a difference in the celebration rites is that the chief carries a sheep for sacrifice to the [[Golden Stool|Stool]].{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=2}} The purification ceremony of [[Odwira festival|Odwira]] is celebrated during Adae Kese at the burial shrines of ancestral spirits. Generally, this coincides with the harvest season of [[Yam (vegetable)|yam]], and hence the ritual was also called the ''Yam custom'' by Europeans.{{Sfn|Roy|2005|p=2}} It is celebrated at this season to thank the gods and the ancestors for a good harvest. The season is equally used to outdoor the new yam.\n\nEvery five years, the Adae Kese Festival is hosted by the paramount ruler of the Asante in the capital city of [[Kumasi]], [[Asanteman]], and lasts for two weeks.<ref name=\"AsanteMazama2008\">{{cite book|last1=Asante|first1=Molefi Kete|last2=Mazama|first2=Ama|title=Encyclopedias of African Religion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B667ATiedQkC&pg=PT36|accessdate=21 November 2012|date=26 November 2008|publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-1-4129-3636-1|pages=36\u2013}}</ref> As a formal state celebration, it involves several villages and towns, within a traditional area known as ''Odwira'',<ref name=African/> uniting Ashanti from all walks of life (''Odwira'' means to purify), who attends and embrace the festival.<ref name=\"ghana.travel\"/> [[Asantehene]], the titular ruler of [[Kumasi]], holds a colourful [[durbar (court)|durbar]] of chiefs and their queens on this occasion when they all turn up in full regalia. Dancing to the beats of drums is part of the pageantry. The festival is also the occasion when people pledge their confidence in the present king of the Ashante. Some of the deserving people are given awards of recognition on this occasion. The king also holds a very private celebration within his palace chambers along with the designated members of the royal family and other officials.<ref name=Kese/>\n\n== Commentary on the Talking Drum ==\nAmong other activities that rake place on the day of the festival, the chief is carried through the streets of [[Kumasi]] in procession.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\">{{Cite web|url=https://africanpoems.net/gods-ancestors/the-adae-kese-festival/|title=The Adae Kese Festival|website=africanpoems.net|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> The following version of the drum recitation was written by [[Robert Sutherland Rattray]] in 1923:\n\n<poem>\n\"Oh, Divine Drummer,\nI am scarcely awake and have risen up.\nI, the Ashanti porcupine chief's drummer,\nI am scarcely awake.\nI have made myself to rise up,\nI am about to sound the drum,\nIf you have gone elsewhere and I call you, \nCome;\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThere are swamps, swamps, swamps,\nWhich can swallow up the elephant.\nA river may lie small in the valley\nBetween great hills.\nBut it flows on for ever and ever.\nIf you have gone elsewhere and I call upon you ( the spirit of the elephant)<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nCome.\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nI lay down, but I did not feel sleepy,\nI lay down but my eyes did not close,\nFor three watches of the night.\nI think about my friends who have left me and are asleep,\nAmoafo-Awuku-The cock-the-the old bird whose bones have grown strong.\nFowl, good morning, good morning.\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThe sky is wide, wide, wide,\nThe earth is wide, wide, wide,\nThe one was lifted up,\nThe other was set down,\nIn ancient times, long, long ago.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nSupreme Sky God, upon whom men lean and fall not,\nWe serve you.\nWhen the Sky God shows you anything\nMay you profit by it.\nIf we wish 'white' we get it,\nIf we wish 'red' we get it.\nHim upon whom we lean and do not fall,\nGod, good morning.\nYou whom we serve upon a Saturday,\nGood morning,\nThe fowl has crowed in the morning,\nThe fowl has awakened and crowed,\nVery early,\nThey are addressing me and I shall understand.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nThe stream crosses the path,\nThe oath crosses the stream;\nWhich of them is the elder?\nDid we not cut a path to go and meet this stream?\nThe stream had its origin long, long ago,\nThe stream had its origin in the Creator.\nHe created things,\nPure, pure Tano (refers to the Ashantis principal god)<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\nCome here, Tano;\nHe devours rams,\nTa, the great one, the powerful one\nWhom we serve upon a Monday.<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/>\n\nHe is coming, he is coming,\nLittle by little, slowly, slowly,\nBe careful not to stumble,\nLittle by little, slowly, slowly.\nYou will come and sit down,\nChief, you will come and sit down.\n''Kon! Kon! Kon!''\nThe great man, Osai's son, has sat down.\nThe King has sat down\nHe who destroys towns has sat down,\nHe who never forgives,\nHe has taken a stool and sat down.\"<ref name=\"AutoVV-11\"/></poem>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Adae Festival]]\n*[[Akwasidae Festival]]\n*[[Ashanti Yam Festival]]\n*[[Awukudae Festival]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= Agorsah |first= E. Kofi|title= Religion, Ritual and African Tradition: AfricanFoundations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wd7y1HOYeo0C&pg=PA42&dq=Adae+Kese+Festival&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HTiwUJOvJoTqmAWAqoGoBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Adae%20Kese%20Festival&f=false|accessdate=24 November 2012|year=2010|publisher= AuthorHouse |isbn=9781449005528|pages=42\u201343|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=  Roy|first=  Christian |title= Religion Traditional festivals. 2. M \u2013 Z |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKqOUfqt4cIC&pg=PA2&dq=Adae+Kese+Festival&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HTiwUJOvJoTqmAWAqoGoBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Adae%20Kese%20Festival&f=false\n|accessdate=24 November 2012|year=2005|publisher= ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781576070895|page=2|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Ashanti people]]\n[[Category:Cultural festivals in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Ashanti Region]]\n[[Category:Yam festivals]]\n[[Category:Religious festivals in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Folk festivals in Ghana]]\n", "name_user": "JalenFolf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removing link(s) to \"Europeans\":WP:OLINK. (TW))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adae_Kese_Festival"}
{"title_page": "Edith Cavell Hospital", "text_new": "{{About|the former Edith Cavell Hospital|the present-day hospital|Peterborough City Hospital}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Edith Cavell Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image      = <!-- optional -->\n| Caption    = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo       = \n| Logo Size = 100px\n| Location   = Bretton Gate\n| Region     = Peterborough\n| State      = Cambs. [[PE postcode area|PE]]3 9GZ\n| Country    = England\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| Type       = District general\n| Speciality = <!-- optional -->\n| Emergency  = No accident & emergency\n| Affiliation= <!-- optional -->\n| Beds       = 153\n| Founded    = 1988\n| Closed     = 2010\n| Website    ={{URL|http://www.peterboroughandstamford.nhs.uk/}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Cambridgeshire\n| map_caption=Location in Cambridgeshire\n}}\nThe '''Edith Cavell Hospital''' was an acute hospital serving the city of [[Peterborough]] and north [[Cambridgeshire]], east [[Northamptonshire]] and [[Rutland]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. Situated on a [[greenfield land|greenfield]] site at [[Westwood, Peterborough|Westwood]], Peterborough, it was decommissioned in late 2010 and demolished in early 2011.<ref>Baker, John [http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/health/edith-cavell-hospital-doors-close-for-the-last-time-1-1667069 Edith Cavell Hospital: Doors close for the last time] Peterborough Evening Telegraph, 19 November 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nOpened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] in 1988, the \u00a320m hospital was built to complement services provided elsewhere in the city and [[List of dedications to Edith Cavell|named after]] the [[Norfolk]]-born nurse and humanitarian, [[Edith Cavell]], who received part of her education at Laurel Court in the [[Peterborough Cathedral|Minster Precinct]].<ref>Daunton, Claire [http://oxforddnb.com/view/article/32330 Cavell, Edith Louisa (1865\u20131915)] ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' Oxford University Press, 2004 (subscription required {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/32330}}, retrieved 30 April 2007)</ref>\n\nThe 153-bed facility also contained three wards and a day activity centre for patients with [[mental health]] problems. These services were managed independently by the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust, based at [[Fulbourn Hospital]] in [[Cambridge]]. The Robert Horrell [[Macmillan Cancer Support|Macmillan Day Centre]], which opened in 1991, was located on site and offered [[palliative care]] to patients living with [[cancer]]. [[Emergency department|Casualty]] and [[Childbirth|maternity]] services were based at nearby [[Peterborough District Hospital]] in [[West Town, Peterborough|West Town]].<ref>Gray, Hannah [http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/peterborough/The-history-of-Peterborough-hospitals.4258597.jp The history of Peterborough hospitals] Peterborough Evening Telegraph, 4 July 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, as part of the \u00a3300 million Greater Peterborough health investment plan, the city's two hospitals transferred to a single site on the Edith Cavell grounds, with the aim of providing a flexible facility more suited to modern healthcare.<ref>[http://www.healthplan.org.uk/ Greater Peterborough Health Investment Plan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093718/http://healthplan.org.uk/ |date=8 January 2008 }} Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Peterborough Primary Care Trust and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust (retrieved 23 April 2007)</ref> The full planning application for the redevelopment of the Edith Cavell site was approved by the council in 2006<ref>[http://www.healthplan.org.uk/ Greater Peterborough Health Investment Plan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093718/http://healthplan.org.uk/ |date=8 January 2008 }} Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Peterborough Primary Care Trust and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust (retrieved 23 April 2007)</ref> and the name [[Peterborough City Hospital]] chosen by public competition in 2008. Together with the adjacent mental health unit, known as the Cavell Centre, it now forms the [[Edith Cavell Healthcare Campus]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nhs.uk/Services/clinics/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=101012|title=Cavell Centre|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[East of England Ambulance Service]]\n*[[Healthcare in Cambridgeshire]]\n*[[List of hospitals in England]]\n*[[Shelf (sexual health service), Peterborough]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.peterboroughandstamford.nhs.uk/ Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080113051211/http://www.peterborough.nhs.uk/ Peterborough Primary Care Trust]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080201030805/http://www.cambsmh.nhs.uk/ Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership NHS Trust]\n*[http://www.eastamb.nhs.uk/ East of England Ambulance Service NHS Trust]\n\n{{Peterborough}}\n{{coord|52.588304|N|0.278466|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1988]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Peterborough]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1988]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the former Edith Cavell Hospital|the present-day hospital|Peterborough City Hospital}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Edith Cavell Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image      = <!-- optional -->\n| Caption    = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo       = \n| Logo Size = 100px\n| Location   = Bretton Gate\n| Region     = Peterborough\n| State      = Cambs. [[PE postcode area|PE]]3 9GZ\n| Country    = England\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]]\n| Type       = District general\n| Speciality = <!-- optional -->\n| Emergency  = No accident & emergency\n| Affiliation= <!-- optional -->\n| Beds       = 153\n| Founded    = 1988\n| Closed     = 2010\n| Website    ={{URL|http://www.peterboroughandstamford.nhs.uk/}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Cambridgeshire\n| map_caption=Location in Cambridgeshire\n}}\nThe '''Edith Cavell Hospital''' was an acute hospital serving the city of [[Peterborough]] and north [[Cambridgeshire]], east [[Northamptonshire]] and [[Rutland]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. Situated on a [[greenfield land|greenfield]] site at [[Westwood, Peterborough|Westwood]], Peterborough, it was decommissioned in late 2010 and demolished in early 2011.<ref>Baker, John [http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/health/edith-cavell-hospital-doors-close-for-the-last-time-1-1667069 Edith Cavell Hospital: Doors close for the last time] Peterborough Evening Telegraph, 19 November 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nOpened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] in 1988, the \u00a320m hospital was built to complement services provided elsewhere in the city and [[List of dedications to Edith Cavell|named after]] the [[Norfolk]]-born nurse and humanitarian, [[Edith Cavell]], who received part of her education at Laurel Court in the [[Peterborough Cathedral|Minster Precinct]].<ref>Daunton, Claire [http://oxforddnb.com/view/article/32330 Cavell, Edith Louisa (1865\u20131915)] ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' Oxford University Press, 2004 (subscription required {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/32330}}, retrieved 30 April 2007)</ref>\n\nThe 153-bed facility also contained three wards and a day activity centre for patients with [[mental health]] problems. These services were managed independently by the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust, based at [[Fulbourn Hospital]] in [[Cambridge]]. The Robert Horrell [[Macmillan Cancer Support|Macmillan Day Centre]], which opened in 1991, was located on site and offered [[palliative care]] to patients living with [[cancer]]. [[Emergency department|Casualty]] and [[Childbirth|maternity]] services were based at nearby [[Peterborough District Hospital]] in [[West Town, Peterborough|West Town]].<ref>Gray, Hannah [http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/peterborough/The-history-of-Peterborough-hospitals.4258597.jp The history of Peterborough hospitals] Peterborough Evening Telegraph, 4 July 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, as part of the \u00a3300 million Greater Peterborough health investment plan, the city's two hospitals transferred to a single site on the Edith Cavell grounds, with the aim of providing a flexible facility more suited to modern healthcare.<ref>[http://www.healthplan.org.uk/ Greater Peterborough Health Investment Plan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093718/http://healthplan.org.uk/ |date=8 January 2008 }} Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Peterborough Primary Care Trust and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust (retrieved 23 April 2007)</ref> The full planning application for the redevelopment of the Edith Cavell site was approved by the council in 2006<ref>[http://www.healthplan.org.uk/ Greater Peterborough Health Investment Plan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108093718/http://healthplan.org.uk/ |date=8 January 2008 }} Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, Peterborough Primary Care Trust and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership Trust (retrieved 23 April 2007)</ref> and the name [[Peterborough City Hospital]] chosen by public competition in 2008. Together with the adjacent mental health unit, known as the Cavell Centre, it now forms the [[Edith Cavell Healthcare Campus]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nhs.uk/Services/clinics/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=101012|title=Cavell Centre|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[East of England Ambulance Service]]\n*[[Healthcare in Cambridgeshire]]\n*[[List of hospitals in England]]\n*[[Shelf (sexual health service), Peterborough]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.peterboroughandstamford.nhs.uk/ Peterborough and Stamford Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080113051211/http://www.peterborough.nhs.uk/ Peterborough Primary Care Trust]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080201030805/http://www.cambsmh.nhs.uk/ Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Mental Health Partnership NHS Trust]\n*[http://www.eastamb.nhs.uk/ East of England Ambulance Service NHS Trust]\n\n{{Peterborough}}\n{{coord|52.588304|N|0.278466|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1988]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Peterborough]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1988]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edith_Cavell_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Forster Green Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Forster Green Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Belfast Health and Social Care Trust]]\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| Image = Forster Green Hospital.jpg\n| Caption = Forster Green Hospital\n| Location = Saintfield Road\n| Region=Belfast\n| State = [[Northern Ireland]]\n| Country = United Kingdom\n| HealthCare = [[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]]\n| Type = Specialist\n| Emergency = No\n| Speciality = Neurology, Care of Older People\n| Founded = 1897\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| Website = {{URL|http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/hospitals/ForsterGreenHospital.htm}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type=Northern Ireland\n| map_caption=Shown in Northern Ireland\n| coordinates={{coord|54.5618|-5.9081|type:landmark_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Forster Green Hospital''' ({{lang-ga|Ospid\u00e9al Forster Green}}) is a non-acute hospital located in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], it offers a range of services including [[neurology]], care of older people and a child and family centre. The hospital is located in a 47-acre site in South Belfast. It is managed by [[Belfast Health and Social Care Trust]]. Also located within the hospital grounds is the regional child and adolescent mental health inpatients unit Beechcroft - this opened in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/about/1499.htm|title=Beechcroft Open Days - New Child and Adolescent Mental Health Inpatient Unit|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref>  Knockbreda Wellbeing and Treatment centre is also located within the grounds of Forster Green and this opened  in 2009. This has been described as a \"one stop approach\" to healthcare which offers a wide range of healthcare services to the local community from [[general practitioner]]s to [[Physical therapy|physiotherapists]] all in the same location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/contact/WellbeingTreatmentCentres.htm|title=Wellbeing and Treatment Centres|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.penoyreprasad.com/project/the-knockbreda-centre/|title=The Knockbreda Centre - Penoyre & Prasad|work=Penoyre & Prasad|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe hospital was founded by [[Forster Green]], a tea and coffee merchant who purchased Fortbreda House and the surrounding grounds for a total sum of \u00a311,000 in 1895 with the plan to build a hospital specifically for the treatment of consumption and chest complaints. Green was aware of the challenges posed by the setting up and running of a hospital as he was a life governor of the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast]]. At the time one of the only treatments for tuberculosis was access to fresh air,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/564540.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} HEALTH {{!}} TB: The sandbag and fresh air cure|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref> this was one of the reasons why the Fortbreda site, with its location at the time being outside the city in relative countryside, was a perfect location for a consumption unit.  Over the subsequent two years the site was developed and on 30 September 1897 Forster Green Hospital for Consumption and Chest Diseases opened.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Forster Green Hospital: caring over the century|last=Wallace|first=Duncan|publisher=|year=2007|isbn=|location=Belfast|pages=6\u20139, 36, 41\u201342, 55, 67\u201368, 74\u201379, 86, 97, 119\u2013121}}</ref>\n\nIn the early years the main purpose of the hospital was to function as a [[sanatorium]]. This meant that most of the patients in the hospital were long term patients who had tuberculosis (TB) or related respiratory illnesses. Before the discovery of [[antibiotic]]s the main methods used to treat TB were; exposure to fresh air, rest and surgery to remove infected parts of the lung- this was seen as a last effort to control the disease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Odell|first=John A.|date=August 2012|title=The history of surgery for pulmonary tuberculosis|journal=Thoracic Surgery Clinics|volume=22|issue=3|pages=257\u2013269|doi=10.1016/j.thorsurg.2012.05.003|issn=1558-5069|pmid=22789591}}</ref> The large amount of open space on the Forster Green site, and the fact it was located outside of the city centre meant that it was the ideal location for the desired non-interventional treatment options.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOver the next 20 years, the hospital steadily grew in size and in 1925 the first x-ray machine was acquired for the hospital- this was used for the diagnosis of thoracic disease and also to help guide treatment. In 1933 the hospital opened a new wing, this increased bed numbers but more notable was that the new wing had operating theatres, this allowed surgical treatment of chest diseases to occur on site. In 1945 the x-ray machinery was upgraded, this boosted the hospitals diagnostic repertoire. Upon the nationwide introduction of the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, the hospital name was officially changed to Forster Green Hospital. A new [[thoracic surgery]] unit was approved for development in 1953 and was finished and operational in 1955, this increased number of surgeries than could be performed in the hospital. Three years later in 1958 a newly built administration unit was opened, this helped better organise the daily workings of the hospital- this building was acquired by the Belfast Trust [[Dietetics]] Service in 2008. Also in 1958 laboratory services were added to the site along with a mortuary, the mortuary was taken over by the Belfast Trust in 1973 and became the Belfast City Mortuary, this was relocated to the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital]] in the 2008 to a new forensic mortuary building costing \u00a34.5 million.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/weekend/why-i-owe-my-career-to-sherlock-holmes-28448510.html|title=Why I owe my career to Sherlock Holmes|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-14|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nA change of direction in the hospital's history occurred in 1983 with the closure of the respiratory medicine wards with these wards being moved to the recently opened [[Belfast City Hospital]] tower block along with the radiology department. The thoracic surgery unit was also closed this year and relocated to the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital.]] Upon the closure of wards specific to the care of older people in [[Belvoir Park Hospital]], [[Musgrave Park Hospital]] and Ulster Hospital, new facilities for care of older people was opened in the hospital in the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Geriatric medicine: the anatomy of change|first1=I C |last1=Taylor|first2=J G |last2=McConnell|date= 2 August 1994|journal=Ulster Medical Journal|pmc=2448767|pmid=8650829|volume=63|issue=2|pages = 162\u20139}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 a specialist rehabilitation unit was opened in the hospital, this unit dealt exclusively with patients with serious brain injuries. This unit was moved to a newly built specialist centre in 2006 - the Regional Acquired Brain Injury Unit which is located in Musgrave Park Hospital.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/incoming/injuries-to-brain-to-be-treated-at-new-centre-28103252.html|title=Injuries to brain to be treated at new centre|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-16|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n\n=== Current services ===\nThe hospital today is significantly smaller than it was in the past. The hospital has two wards for neurology patients- wards 3 and 4. Wards 5 and 6 are used for care of older patients and ward 7 is the child and family centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/hospitals/FGH_ComingIntoHospital.htm|title=Coming into Hospital|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Beechcroft ===\nAlso located within the Forster Green Hospital site is Beechcroft- the regional child and adolescent mental health inpatient unit, the only unit of its type in Northern Ireland. This unit opened in early 2010 and was built at a cost of \u00a39 million. It deals with patients with complex needs and offers a range of assessment and treatment options that cannot be done within the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.familysupportni.gov.uk/listing/camhs-tier-4-beechcroft-belfast-trust/|title=Child and Adolescent In-Patient Unit (Regional Service) - Beechcroft - FamilySupportNI.gov.ukFamilySupportNI.gov.uk|website=www.familysupportni.gov.uk|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/new-mental-health-care-facility-opens-28521418.html|title=New mental health care facility opens|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-16|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Belfast Health and Social Care Trust}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1897]]\n[[Category:Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in County Down]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Forster Green Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Belfast Health and Social Care Trust]]\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| Image = Forster Green Hospital.jpg\n| Caption = Forster Green Hospital\n| Location = Saintfield Road\n| Region=Belfast\n| State = [[Northern Ireland]]\n| Country = United Kingdom\n| HealthCare = [[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]]\n| Type = Specialist\n| Emergency = No\n| Speciality = Neurology, Care of Older People\n| Founded = 1897\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| Website = {{URL|http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/hospitals/ForsterGreenHospital.htm}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type=Northern Ireland\n| map_caption=Shown in Northern Ireland\n| coordinates={{coord|54.5618|-5.9081|type:landmark_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Forster Green Hospital''' ({{lang-ga|Ospid\u00e9al Forster Green}}) is a non-acute hospital located in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], it offers a range of services including [[neurology]], care of older people and a child and family centre. The hospital is located in a 47-acre site in South Belfast. It is managed by [[Belfast Health and Social Care Trust]]. Also located within the hospital grounds is the regional child and adolescent mental health inpatients unit Beechcroft - this opened in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/about/1499.htm|title=Beechcroft Open Days - New Child and Adolescent Mental Health Inpatient Unit|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref>  Knockbreda Wellbeing and Treatment centre is also located within the grounds of Forster Green and this opened  in 2009. This has been described as a \"one stop approach\" to healthcare which offers a wide range of healthcare services to the local community from [[general practitioner]]s to [[Physical therapy|physiotherapists]] all in the same location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/contact/WellbeingTreatmentCentres.htm|title=Wellbeing and Treatment Centres|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.penoyreprasad.com/project/the-knockbreda-centre/|title=The Knockbreda Centre - Penoyre & Prasad|work=Penoyre & Prasad|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe hospital was founded by [[Forster Green]], a tea and coffee merchant who purchased Fortbreda House and the surrounding grounds for a total sum of \u00a311,000 in 1895 with the plan to build a hospital specifically for the treatment of consumption and chest complaints. Green was aware of the challenges posed by the setting up and running of a hospital as he was a life