s of thoracic disease and also to help guide treatment. In 1933 the hospital opened a new wing, this increased bed numbers but more notable was that the new wing had operating theatres, this allowed surgical treatment of chest diseases to occur on site. In 1945 the x-ray machinery was upgraded, this boosted the hospitals diagnostic repertoire. Upon the nationwide introduction of the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, the hospital name was officially changed to Forster Green Hospital. A new [[thoracic surgery]] unit was approved for development in 1953 and was finished and operational in 1955, this increased number of surgeries than could be performed in the hospital. Three years later in 1958 a newly built administration unit was opened, this helped better organise the daily workings of the hospital- this building was acquired by the Belfast Trust [[Dietetics]] Service in 2008. Also in 1958 laboratory services were added to the site along with a mortuary, the mortuary was taken over by the Belfast Trust in 1973 and became the Belfast City Mortuary, this was relocated to the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital]] in the 2008 to a new forensic mortuary building costing \u00a34.5 million.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/weekend/why-i-owe-my-career-to-sherlock-holmes-28448510.html|title=Why I owe my career to Sherlock Holmes|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-14|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nA change of direction in the hospital's history occurred in 1983 with the closure of the respiratory medicine wards with these wards being moved to the recently opened [[Belfast City Hospital]] tower block along with the radiology department. The thoracic surgery unit was also closed this year and relocated to the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital.]] Upon the closure of wards specific to the care of older people in [[Belvoir Park Hospital]], [[Musgrave Park Hospital]] and Ulster Hospital, new facilities for care of older people was opened in the hospital in the late 1980s and early 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Geriatric medicine: the anatomy of change|first1=I C |last1=Taylor|first2=J G |last2=McConnell|date= 2 August 1994|journal=Ulster Medical Journal|pmc=2448767|pmid=8650829|volume=63|issue=2|pages = 162\u20139}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 a specialist rehabilitation unit was opened in the hospital, this unit dealt exclusively with patients with serious brain injuries. This unit was moved to a newly built specialist centre in 2006 - the Regional Acquired Brain Injury Unit which is located in Musgrave Park Hospital.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/incoming/injuries-to-brain-to-be-treated-at-new-centre-28103252.html|title=Injuries to brain to be treated at new centre|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-16|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n\n=== Current services ===\nThe hospital today is significantly smaller than it was in the past. The hospital has two wards for neurology patients- wards 3 and 4. Wards 5 and 6 are used for care of older patients and ward 7 is the child and family centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.belfasttrust.hscni.net/hospitals/FGH_ComingIntoHospital.htm|title=Coming into Hospital|website=www.belfasttrust.hscni.net|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Beechcroft ===\nAlso located within the Forster Green Hospital site is Beechcroft- the regional child and adolescent mental health inpatient unit, the only unit of its type in Northern Ireland. This unit opened in early 2010 and was built at a cost of \u00a39 million. It deals with patients with complex needs and offers a range of assessment and treatment options that cannot be done within the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.familysupportni.gov.uk/listing/camhs-tier-4-beechcroft-belfast-trust/|title=Child and Adolescent In-Patient Unit (Regional Service) - Beechcroft - FamilySupportNI.gov.ukFamilySupportNI.gov.uk|website=www.familysupportni.gov.uk|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/new-mental-health-care-facility-opens-28521418.html|title=New mental health care facility opens|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2018-09-16|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Belfast Health and Social Care Trust}}\n[[Category:Hospitals in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1897]]\n[[Category:Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in County Down]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forster_Green_Hospital"}
